<h1>About</h1>

<div class="about">
  <p>
    I'm Mukund Chopra. I built one of the largest apartment locating operations in the US. At peak, we process 30,000 leads a day across multiple metro areas — Dallas, Houston, Austin, Denver, Chicago, and growing. Most of that volume is handled by AI systems I designed and built myself.
  </p>
  <p>
    I started HomeEasy in my twenties with no technical background. Taught myself to code because I couldn't afford engineers. Then taught myself machine learning because I couldn't afford data scientists. Then replaced most of the engineering work with AI because I realized the AI was better at it than the contractors I was hiring.
  </p>
  <p>
    Today, the entire operation runs on systems I built with AI as my engineering team. The humans who remain handle phone calls and apartment tours — the two things that still require a physical presence or a real voice. Everything else is automated: lead qualification, document processing, inventory management, commission tracking, compliance, follow-up, recruiting.
  </p>
  <p>
    The Tiger Global thesis — infinite revenue at near-zero marginal cost — isn't theoretical for me. I've been living it. We hit 97% contribution margins in an industry where 20% is considered healthy. Not by cutting corners. By removing the humans from processes that never needed humans in the first place.
  </p>
  <p>
    I've spent years saying no to people who asked about the technology. Partners, investors, folks in adjacent industries who saw what we were doing and wanted to know how. I wasn't ready. The systems needed to prove themselves in production first, at scale, over years — not months.
  </p>
  <p>
    They have. So now I'm open to conversation.
  </p>
  <p>
    agent-ic is my private technology studio. It's not a company. It's not a fund. It's a place to think in public about what happens when you apply the Amazon's Own Customer playbook to offline brokerage — and to have direct conversations with people who find that interesting.
  </p>

